section.t:
If the data model consists only of this module, then the
      following is a valid JSON-encoded configuration:


    {
      "foomod:top": {
        "foo": 54
      }
    }

Now, assume the container "top" is augmented from another
      module, "barmod":

        &barmod.yang;

A valid JSON-encoded configuration containing both leafs may
      then look like this:


    {
      "foomod:top": {
        "foo": 54,
        "barmod:bar": true
      }
    }

Example: For the leaf node definition


    leaf foo {
      type uint8;
    }


        the following is a valid JSON-encoded instance:


    "foo": 123

Example: For the container definition


    container bar {
      leaf foo {
        type uint8;
      }
    }


        the following is a valid instance:


    "bar": {
      "foo": 123
    }

Example: For the leaf-list definition


    leaf-list foo {
      type uint8;
    }


        the following is a valid instance:


    "foo": [123, 0]

Example: For the list definition


    list bar {
      key foo;
      leaf foo {
        type uint8;
      }
      leaf baz {
        type string;
      }
    }


        the following is a valid instance:


    "bar": [
      {
        "foo": 123,
        "baz": "zig"
      },
      {
        "foo": 0,
        "baz": "zag"
      }
    ]

Example: For the anyxml definition


    anyxml bar;


        the following is a valid instance:


    "bar": [true, null, true]}

figure.artwork:
module exmod {
  ...
  import ietf-interfaces {
    prefix if;
  }
  import iana-if-type {
    prefix ianaift;
  }
  ...
  leaf type {
    type identityref {
      base "if:interface-type";
    }
  }
}

section.t:
Example: For the leaf definition


    leaf foo {
      type empty;
    }


        a valid instance is


    "foo": [null]

For example, consider the following YANG definition:


    leaf bar {
      type union {
        type uint16;
        type string;
      }
    }


        In RESTCONF , it is
        then fully acceptable to set the value of "bar" in the
        following way when using the "application/yang.data+xml" media
        type:


    <bar>13.5</bar>


        because the value may be interpreted as a string, i.e., the
        second member type of the union. When using the
        "application/yang.data+json" media type, however, this is an error:


    "bar": 13.5


        In this case, the JSON encoding indicates the value is
        supposed to be a number rather than string.
